{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = Harriet Malinowitz | image = | caption = |birth_name=Harriet Malinowitz | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = Academic, Professor of English, Scholar | spouse = | notableworks = ''Textual Orientations:Lesbian and Gay Students and the Making of Discourse Communities'' | genre = [[queer theory]], [[ethnography]], [[rhetorical studies]], [[liberatory pedagogy]] | website =}}
'''Harriet Malinowitz''' is an American academic scholar specializing in lesbian and gay issues in higher education, [[women's studies]], the rhetoric of Zionism and Palestine, and writing theory and [[pedagogy]].
==Life and work== A Professor of English at Long Island University, Malinowitz earned her Ph.D. from New York University.<ref>{{cite web|title=Richard L. Conolly College of Liberal Arts and Sciences: Faculty|url=http://www.liu.edu/Brooklyn/Academics/Faculty/Faculty/M/Harriet-Malinowitz|website=Long Island University|publisher=Long Island University|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref>
Notable works by Malinowitz include ''Textual Orientiations: Lesbian and Gay Students and the Making of Discourse Communities'' (Heinemann, 1995), an ethnographic study focusing on the community emerging in a college course that examines lesbian and gay experience. ''Textual Orientations'' highlights the productive intersections of two academic fields: [[composition studies|rhetoric and composition]] and [[lesbian and gay studies]] while providing a pedagogical model that values the "vantage point of the social margin."<ref>{{cite book|last1=Malinowitz|first1=Harriet|title=Textual Orientations: Lesbian and Gay Students and the Making of Discourse Communities|date=1995|publisher=Boynton/Cook Publishers: Heinemann|location=Portsmouth, NH|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref>
Malinowitz is also a writer of lesbian [[stand-up comedy]], most notably for her partner Sara Cytron's shows ''A Dyke Grows in Brooklyn'' and ''Take My Domestic Partner--Please!''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Haggerty|first1=George|last2=Zimmerman|first2=Bonnie|title=Encyclopedia of Lesbian and Gay Histories|date=2000|publisher=Garland|location=New York|page=XXXV|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref>
